# OpsGate Skill

Use the managed OpsGate submit handler.

## Scope

This v1 integration can do exactly one thing:

- create a new OpsGate ticket
- with exactly one `investigator` step
- using agent `codex`
- still requiring normal OpsGate approval before execution

Do not use this skill for arbitrary multi-step workflows or implementer/reviewer plans. If the user explicitly wants a richer workflow, explain that they must create or edit that workflow in OpsGate directly.

## Input Contract

User input is everything after `/{{ openclaw_opsgate_command_skill_name }}`.

- `create [--title <text>] [--task-ref <text>] <issue description>`

Natural-language mapping:

- If the user asks to "create/file/submit an OpsGate ticket", convert the current issue into one concise issue description and run `create <issue description>`.
- If the user already gave a good short title, pass it via `--title`.
- If the user provided a stable external reference (incident/check/task id), pass it via `--task-ref`.

## Safety Rules

- Only use facts already present in the conversation or current tool results.
- Do not include secrets, tokens, passwords, or raw credential values.
- Do not claim the ticket is approved or already running.
- Keep the ticket framed as investigation only; do not encode implementation/deploy instructions as the requested action.

## Execution Rules

Always execute exactly one command:

```bash
{{ openclaw_opsgate_container_skills_dir }}/{{ openclaw_opsgate_skill_name }}/handler.py <raw-user-input>
```

When no input is provided, return:

`Usage: /{{ openclaw_opsgate_command_skill_name }} create [--title <text>] [--task-ref <text>] <issue description>`

Return the handler output as-is.
